column12: FABRICATION SYSTEM FOR CONTINUOUSLY FABRICATING GRADED EXTENDED LENGTH LUMBER WITH MAXIMUM GRADE UTILIZATION OF INPUT LOW QUALITY RAW LUMBER
column13: An extended length graded lumber fabrication system features a number of fabrication stages along a substantially continuous fabrication path providi ng high through put fabrication of graded lumber of extended length from low quality raw lumber. The fabrication stages include reject recognition stages, a supply lumber grading stage, a finger jointing stage and a final grading stage for the extended length lumber. The fabrication system is configured in conjunction with the particularities of low quality raw lumber to minimize grade fluctuations, increase grade bandwidth and minimize raw lumber waste during fabrication of extended length graded lumber, which may be used in wooden truss joists. The use of l ow quality raw lumber cut from small diameter tree trunks is environmentally beneficial. It contributes to preserve old growth and to use lighter and environmentally less invasive timber harvesting machinery and techniques.

1,151,223. Fluid-pressure brakes. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 7 July, 1966 [15 July, 1965], No. 29998/65. Heading F2F. In a compressed-air or vacuum brake system for the tractor portion of a tractor/trailer vehicle, each of the rear wheel brake cylinders 9, 10 is provided with two chambers 14, 15, the former being connected with the driver's valve 6, which is supplied by a reservoir 5, and the latter being connected via an anti-skid valve unit 20 to either atmosphere or an anti-skid reservoir 18 which is isolated from the reservoir 5 by a check valve 4, the arrangement operating such that when a skid is imminent the valve unit 20 operates to cut off the connection of chambers 15 to atmosphere and to connect them instead to the reservoir 18 whereby the brake is released, pressure build-up in the chambers 14 during operation of the valve unit 20 being prevented by balanced exhaust valves 56. The embodiments described are compressed-air systems. In the embodiment of Fig. 1, the valve unit 20 also controls the supply of compressed-air to the chambers 14, cutting off the supply when a skid is imminent. When a skid-correcting pressure is supplied by the valve unit 20 to the chambers 15, the resultant pressure rise in chambers 14 overcomes the combined effect of the pressure in the lines 60, which are now isolated by the valve unit 20, and springs 59, so that pistons 57 are moved to open exhaust valves 61 which relieve the pressure. The valves 56 also act as quick-release valves during release of the brakes, A ball-valve 64 in each piston 57 prevents release of pressure from the chambers 14 except by way of the exhaust valves 61, but allows flow of air into the chambers 14. Instead of or in addition to the isolating effect of the valve unit 20 on the air supplied to chambers 14, a sensitivity control valve 70, Fig. 4, may be incorporated in the system, its inlet 74 being connected with the driver's valve 6 while its outlet 73 is connected either directly or via the valve unit 20 to the chambers 14. The valve 70 is responsive to a control pressure at 80 which is conveniently obtained from that used to control the position of the spool 23 of the valve unit 20 where, as shown in Fig. 1, valve unit 20 is a two-stage valve having a primary valve 21 which is operated mechanically by the control-rod 22 of an inertia unit (not shown), driven by the vehicle transmission and which determines the control pressure. The control pressure passes via a check valve 78 of the valve 70 to a chamber 77 where it controls the position of a spring-loaded restrictor member 75 so as to determine the throttling effect of a waisted central portion 85 of the restrictor member on the air passing between inlet 74 and outlet 73, whereby should the driver maintain a heavy pressure on the brake pedal, pressure in chambers 14 and 15 is not allowed to build up too quickly and so reduce the differential between the pressures in chambers 14 and 15 during a sustained skid correction. When valve 70 is used, the valve unit 20 may be simplified by omitting its function of isolating the air supplied to chambers 14 (Fig. 5, not shown). Alternative means for ensuring that pressure in reservoir 18 is always higher than the pressure supplied to chambers 14 comprises the provision of a pressure-balancing valve (170, Figs. 11, 12, not shown) between the driver's valve 6 and the valve unit 20 of the Fig. 1 embodiment which limits the pressure supplied to chambers 14 to a value below the pressure in reservoir 18. In another embodiment (Fig. 6, not shown) a sensitivity valve (101) similar to the valve 70 is used in conjunction with a single-stage anti-skid valve unit 100, Fig. 7, which comprises coaxial plungers 105, 109, slidable in a sleeve 107 and urged away from one another and from an adjustable top cap 108 by springs 110, 111. When plunger 22 of the anti-skid device moves upwards, an exhaust valve 117, 118 is first closed and an inlet valve 120, 121 then opens to perform the change-over of chambers 15 from atmospheric pressure to that supplied by the reservoir 18. The positions of the valve seats 118, 120 are simultaneously adjusted by adjustment of the cap 108, which includes an exhaust flap 115, movement of the cap in turn causing the sleeve 107 to be adjusted. Alternatively, individual adjustment of both inlet and exhaust valves may be provided (Figs. 8, 9, not shown). Exhausting of the chambers 15 may be accelerated by the provision of a quickrelease valve (160, Fig. 10, not shown). Where the pressure-limiting valve (170, Figs. 11, 12, not shown) referred to above is used in conjunction with a two-stage valve unit 20, a pressure-reducing valve 190, Fig. 13, may also be included between the reservoir 18 and the primary valve of the valve unit 20 to control the pressure in the chambers 15 in accordance with the pressure of air being supplied to the chambers 14. The valve 190 comprises a diaphragm 196 between two bore portions of different diameter respectively associated with inlet 191 from the reservoir 18 and a connection 191 to the line between valve unit 20 and one of the chambers 14, whereby a valve member 199 attached to the diaphragm moves to engage a valve seat 200 when the pressure at outlet 198 to the primary valve of the valve unit 20 rises to a predetermined value with respect to that being supplied to the chambers 14. The valve 190 includes a check valve 204, 205 to allow release of pressure from the primary valve of the valve unit 20 when air is released from the line feeding the chambers 14, i.e. when the brakes are released. The chambers 14, 15 may either be formed in a single brake cylinder, as shown, by using a filling member (216, Fig. 14, not shown), or may be provided in separate cylinders (Fig. 15, not shown), whose diaphragms are connected to a common brake-operating lever. The brake cylinders may act on the brakes via a master cylinder instead of directly.

column12: Hole Saw Arbor System For Power Drill Assisted Tightening And Loosening
column13: An arbor system includes an arbor, a hole saw, a tightening feature and a tubular wrench. The arbor has a arbor coupling. A clamp body of the hole saw is sandwiched between the arbor coupling and the tightening feature in a pressed contact that is fully form fitting. Operational tilt and load torque are transmitted without affecting the tight-screwed interlocking between thread and tightening feature. Operational cutting vibrations are reduced by increased press contact facilitated by the tubular wrench that axially accesses the tightening feature from a direction opposite the power drill. The tubular wrench provides clearance to the pivot drill and the hole saw and safe handling protected against the hole saw's cutting teeth. Tightening feature and tubular wrench engage in a centering It manner such that the power drill may be used to quickly tighten or loosen the tightening feature while the tubular wrench is fixedly held.

column13: A jackscrew nut and/or bolt head assembly includes a load washer that is interlocked with the main body. Spherical faces at the washer top are thereby held in alignment with corresponding spherical jackscrew bottoms, which assures evenly distributed contact pressures during out of angle elastic jackscrew displacement during jackscrew loading. The load washer interlock may provide further for a transfer of a primary pre tightening torque exerted onto the main body of the nut and/or bolt head. column12: Intermittent feeding technique for increasing the melting rate of polycrystalline silicon
column13: A process for preparing a silicon melt in a crucible for use in growing a single crystal silicon ingot by the Czochralski method. The crucible is first loaded with chunk polycrystalline silicon and heated to partially melt the load. Granular polycrystalline silicon is then fed onto the exposed unmelted chunk polycrystalline silicon to complete the charge of silicon in the crucible. The granular polycrystalline silicon is intermittently delivered using a plurality of alternating on-periods and off-periods. During each on-period, granular polycrystalline silicon is flowed through a feed device that directs the granular polycrystalline silicon onto the unmelted chunk polycrystalline silicon. During each off-period, the flow of the granular polycrystalline silicon is interrupted. The loaded chunk polycrystalline silicon and the fed granular polycrystalline silicon are melted to form the silicon melt.

column12: Thermoplastic moulding materials based on a styrene-acrylonitrile copolymer, an elastomer and a polyimide.
column13: The invention relates to the field of thermoplastic moulding materials, more particularly the use of elastomers to modify such materials to improve their impact resistance. A problem with this approach is that when elastomers are blended with thermoplastic polymers such as styrene/ acrylonitrile copolymers the flexural strength of the material is considerably reduced. The invention provides a thermoplastic moulding material comprising styrene/acrylonitrile copolymer, an elastomeric material having an elongation at break greater than the styrene/acrylonitrile copolymer, a polyimide pre- polymer and a reinforcing filler. The polyimide prepolymer is an addition polyimide prepared from a polyamine and a bis-imide of an unsaturated carboxylic acid. The reinforcing filler is glass fibre or mica, although other fillers may be included along with these. The elastomeric material may be a sulphur vulcanizable rubber or a thermoplastic rubber. if vulcanizable, the rubber is preferably used uncured. Use of the moulding material is in the manufacture of moulded plastics articles.

In a friction brake the retraction of a friction member from a co-operating surface in the off position of the brake is effected by the engagement of a retraction device at all times with a part of a resilient member which engages with the material of the friction member. In the disc brake illustrated, in Fig. 3, each friction pad 17 is engaged at its periphery by a resilient finger 26 of a resilient steel spring strip 23, the finger 26 urging it away from the disc surface, the movement of the finger being limited to the amount permitted by slot 27 in a web 25 of a plate bolted to the calliper housing; the clearance being only sufficient to provide a predetermined clearance between the pad and the disc. When the pad wears and its movement towards the disc becomes greater than that permitted to the finger by the slot 27, the pointed end of the finger ploughs a groove in the friction material during the excess part of the pad movement so that it takes up a fresh position in the pad displaced from the previous position by an amount equal to the pad wear. On release of the brake the finger again retracts the pad through the distance permitted by slot 27 so that a substantially constant clearance between the pad and the disc is maintained through the life of the pad. A second finger 28 may be provided on the inner side of the pad to ensure even engagement thereof. Instead of engaging beneath the surface of the friction material, the end of the finger 36 may be made flat (Fig. 7), to bear against the surface of the pads instead of ploughing grooves therein. METHOD AND SENSOR FOR CAPTURING RATE AND POSITION AND STABILIZATION OF A SATELLITE USING AT LEAST ONE FOCAL PLANE
column13: An optical sensor includes dual fields of view including a panoramic field of view spanning 360 in azimuth angle in a direction perpendicular to an axis of the sensor, and a limb-looking field of view non-perpendicular to the axis for viewing the limb of the earth. Both fields of view are imaged onto annular regions of one of more focal plane arrays comprising pixels arranged in a rectangular array of rows and columns. The sensor is used in a method for capturing rate and direction of rotation of a satellite about its axes and for detecting orientation of the satellite about two of its axes. Rate and direction are determined by finding the center of the earth relative to axes of the focal plane array based on the image of the earth limb from the panoramic field of view, and comparing the earth center location at a series of sequential times. The rate and position information are used for stabilizing an initially tumbling satellite after tip-off. Once the satellite is stabilized, its orientation is detected by finding the earth center location on the focal plane array based on the earth limb image from the limb-looking optics of the sensor. In one embodiment of the invention, both fields of view are imaged onto concentric inner and outer ring-shaped regions of the same focal plane array.

column12: Shadow memory system for storing variable backup blocks in consecutive time periods
column13: A highly reliable shadow memory system is able to survive multiple fast sequence power failures and includes a volatile main memory and a shadow memory subsystem which continually monitors write accesses to the main memory. The shadow memory subsystem includes a disk drive or shadow memory storing a copy of the data in main memory. As the main memory contents are altered, the shadow memory is continually updated to reflect the changes while main utility power is available. In the event of a main utility power failure, backup power is required to store main memory data in the shadow memory for only a few storage locations for which the updating of the shadow memory may lag main memory data changes. Consequently, only a small portion of available battery backup power is required to preserve all main memory data and the system can withstand multiple rapid succession power failures without loss of data.

The present invention is a method and apparatus for providing a sculptured effect to a lawn. Each row of grass can be provided with an aesthetically pleasing cross-sectional configuration utilizing the sculpturing blades of the present invention with a standard rotary lawnmower. The blades include relatively short sections of downwardly offset cutting edges along leading edge of each half of the blade. Various blade design configurations are contemplated and two such designs are disclosed as preferred embodiments. After the blade is mounted for rotation with the output shaft of the internal combustion engine of the lawnmower, the lawnmower is started and throttled down to the greatest extent possible without causing the engine to stall as the lawnmower is pushed across the lawn at a normal to brisk walking pace.

column12: OIL EXTRACTION PROCESS AND APPARATUS THEREFOR
column13: A process for solvent extraction of oils, in an extraction chamber, comprises the formation of a solvent mist with significant adiabatic cooling, whereby a pressure difference between the solvent inlet and outlet of the extraction chamber drives the solvent mist through the raw oil bearing. The solvent is fed to the extraction chamber at pressures exceeding atmospheric pressure, and the outlet of the extraction chamber is subject to a partial vacuum. An apparatus for solvent extraction comprises an extraction chamber for receiving oil bearing raw material therein, said extraction chamber comprising a solvent spray injection system connected via an inlet to a high pressure solvent feed circuit portion, said extraction chamber further connected via an outlet to a low pressure circuit portion connected to a gas recovery vacuum pump system.

column12: Methods and Systems for Improving Read Performance in Data De-Duplication Storage
column13: The present invention is directed toward methods and systems for data de-duplication. More particularly, in various embodiments, the present invention provides systems and methods for data de-duplication that may utilize a data de-duplication system that retrieves data from a data storage device in an order based on the location of blocks on the data storage device. Some embodiments break a data stream into multiple blocks of data and store the blocks of data on a data storage device of a data de-duplication system, wherein a code representing a redundant block of data is stored in place of the block of data. A location for each block of data may be stored. Additionally, the blocks may be read in an order that is determined based on the location of the blocks.

column12: AGGRESSIVE DATA DEDUPLICATION USING LAZY GARBAGE COLLECTION
column13: A method for extending data lifetime for reference in deduplication is provided. The method includes determining that a quantity of user data has at least a threshold amount of data that is re-created in a storage system. The method includes protecting at least portions of the quantity of user data from erasure by garbage collection in the storage system during a predetermined time interval, wherein the protected at least portions are available for data deduplication of further user data in the storage system during the predetermined time interval.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR OIL AND FAT EXTRACTION
column13: An apparatus and method for extracting oils and fats from oil-bearing substances without using degrading temperatures. The apparatus may comprise an extraction chamber containing an oil-bearing substance, an oil-collecting chamber, a recovery pump, a first jacket adjacent at least a portion of the extraction chamber, and a second jacket adjacent at least a portion of the oil-collecting chamber. The method involves heating a solvent and reducing pressure to facilitate a low-temperature vacuum boil, delivering the heated solvent into the extraction chamber configured to facilitate the low-temperature vacuum boil of the solvent within the extraction chamber, pumping the solvent in vapor form out of the extraction chamber with the recovery pump, delivering the oil and fat extracted in the extraction chamber to the oil-collecting chamber, pumping solvent in vapor form out of the oil-collecting chamber with the recovery pump, and delivering the solvent received by the recovery pump to the first and second jackets to provide heat to the chambers.

A gearbox comprises a plurality of gear pairs each having a specific gear ratio, and a plurality of selectors each mounted between two gear pairs for selecting one of the two gear pairs, wherein the gear ratio of the selected gear pair is cascaded through an output shaft to another two gear pairs having another selector, and so on. In this way, the effective or aggregate gear ratio of the gearbox is the product of the gear ratios of the selected gear pairs. Thus, the number of available output speeds excluding neutral is given by 2 n , where n=(number of gear pairs)/2.

Laser marking device for serial I-joist cutouts
column13: A laser marking device includes a fixture for temporarily attaching the device in an initial cutout of a number of serial cutouts to be fabricated in adjacent assembled I-joists. Combined with the fixture is an angle gage that provides angular positioning of a marking laser. The angle gage is configured to hold the laser with its beam coinciding with the marking origin of the initial cutout, which in case of circular cutout may be the reference center at which the pilot drill of the hole saw is centered at the begin of the cutout operation. The marker laser may be horizontally and/or vertically oriented together with an eventual alignment laser and an eventual target marker temporarily affixed on the I-joist where a final reference point is determined for an axial orientation of the cutouts across the I-joists.

The frame consists of arches 10, 11, connected by braces 14<1>, 15 and provided with cross-bars 13, 14, perforated feet 12, and curved irons 15<1>, 16, 17 to keep the pigs apart. Normally the lever 26 rests on a pin 30. A rack, consisting of a U- shaped frame 31 provided with cross-bars 36 is pivoted on the bar 33 over which the front edge of the pan is beaded. The rack is held out of contact with the rear edge of the pan, when that is tilted, by means of loops 38. The space between the fronts of the arches 10, 11 is closed by the pan when it is tilted, and may be closed at other times by means of a pivoted quadrantal cover 39, which rests upon the reduced and projecting ends of the cross-bars 13, 14, and may be secured in position on either side of the frame by means of a hasp and staple.

1,156,015. Fluid-pressure brakes. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 11 Aug., 1966 [24 Aug., 1965], No. 36195/65. Heading F2F. A rotary-inertia skid-sensing device for an anti-skid braking system comprises a driving shaft 8 which drives a flywheel 18 through a torque-sensitive coupling consisting of a helical spring 42 arranged within a sleeve 24 secured to the flywheel and extending into a sleeve 21 rotatable independently of both the flywheel and the shaft, the sleeve 21 being coupled to the shaft 8 by a transverse pin 37 passing through openings 38 in a hollow end portion of the shaft which are larger than the diameter of the pin, and the lower end of the sleeve 21 having cam faces 34 engaged with cam faces 33 of an actuating member in the form of a coaxial sleeve 28 which is slidable on splines of the hollow end portion of the shaft 8 so as to rotate with the shaft. A helical tension spring 36 is connected between the second sleeve 28 and the pin 37 such as to act as a torsion spring as well as urging the two sleeves together so that, when the flywheel overruns the shaft as a result of rapid deceleration, relative rotation of the two sleeves is resisted both by the friction between the cam forces 33, 34 caused by the tension in spring 36 and by the torsional force exerted by spring 36. When both these are overcome, the resulting camming action between the faces 33, 34 causes axial movement of the second sleeve 28 which causes it to engage the button 43 of a micro-switch controlling a valve in the fluid circuit of the brakes, or alternatively actuate the valve direct, so as to reduce braking of the associated vehicle wheels. The torsional force exerted by the spring 36 is variable by providing the sleeve 28 with a rotatable end cap 35 to which the adjacent end of the spring is secured, the cap being provided with a flange 44 having a pair of ears 45, 46 which can be bent to engage a series of notches in the sleeve to lock the cap in its adjusted position. The shaft 8 is driven by a gear-wheel 9 engageable with a gear-wheel of the vehicle transmission, the gear-wheel 9 being connected with the shaft 8 so as to provide a predetermined amount of backlash, either by the peg 12 shown which engages a slot in the gear-wheel or by any of the other arrangements described in Specification 1,156,014 which is referred to.

column12: Automotive collision avoidance and/or air bag deployment radar
column13: A Doppler radar system for a vehicle providing driver warning, vehicle brake application and air bag deployment. The system produces voltage level input directed to the distance and approach rate to an object, vehicle speed and driving monitor inputs, such as steering angles, turning rates, braking, and acceleration/deacceleration. These voltages are properly weighted as to their importance. These weighted instantaneous input voltages are summed. The summed voltage is then compared with a predetermined voltage level dividing safe and danger zones. If the summed level falls within the safe zone, the radar system produces no output signals. If the summed voltage level falls within the danger zone, the radar system produces audio warning signals and if impact with an object is eminent vehicles braking signals are then produced. The invention further includes an air bag deployment feature. A vehicle air bag is deployed when the vehicle speed exceeds a pre-determined value and the distance to impact is within a predetermined distance. The air bag deployment and audio and braking functions are independent.

A disc brake comprises a rotatable disc 10, a friction element 27, a deformable element 32 to maintain the element parallel to the braking surface of the disc and a brake-applying member 11, 12 independent of the deformable element for forcing the element into frictional contact with the disc and for taking the torque when the brake is applied. As shown, friction elements 27 are secured to blocks 26 loosely mounted in apertures 24 in the pressure plates 11, 12 which are pivoted at 13 on the fixed support 14. Bolts 30 are threaded into the blocks 26 and are gripped by hooks 33 at the end of the deformable metal beams 32. Operation of the brake is effected by a lever 20 pivoted at 21 on the plate 12. A tie-rod 15 connects the plate 11 to a lever 20 by means of a trunnion block 18 and a nut 19 which may be rotated automatically as wear takes place. If the friction pads 28 which are bonded to metal backing plates 29 are not in full contact on initial application of the brake, the backing plates 29 rock on the convex surface of the plates 11, 12 to accommodate themselves to the disc. The shank of the bolt 30 moves along the hook 33 which grips the shank when the brake is released to retain it in the aligned position. As wear takes place the beams 32 will take on a permanent set but will still retain the bolt 30 in the aligned position and will have enough resilience to withdraw the pads after each brake application.

column12: Process for preparing a silicon melt from a polysilicon charge
column13: A process for preparing a silicon melt from a polysilicon charge, for use in the production of single crystal silicon ingots by the Czochralski method, in a crucible which has a bottom, a sidewall formation, a centerline which is substantially parallel to the sidewall formation and which intersects a geometric centerpoint of the bottom, and a radius extending from the centerline to the sidewall formation. In the process, the crucible is loaded with chunk polysilicon to form a charge having a bowl-like shape, wherein initially the load generally slopes radially upwardly and outwardly from the centerline toward the sidewall formation to an apex and then slopes generally downwardly and outwardly from the apex to the sidewall formation. The bowl-shaped chunk polysilicon charge is heated to form a partially melted charge, and granular polysilicon is fed onto the partially melted charge to form a mixed charge of chunk and granular polysilicon. As the mixed charge is further heated to form a silicon melt, the unmelted chunk polysilicon present above the melt surface acts to deflect any molten silicon that may be splattered as granular polysilicon rapidly melts and hydrogen is released.

1,113,595. Fluid-pressure brakes; disc brakes. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 18 Aug., 1965 [26 Aug., 1964], No. 34859/64. Headings F2E and F2F. An anti-skid fluid pressure control device for a brake in which a friction member is movable circumferentially to a limited extent under the drag force, particularly a spot-type disc brake having its caliper 3 arranged for limited rotation about the axis of the disc 1, as by rotatably mounting it on a support 2, comprises a valve for reducing the pressure in cylinders 6 of the caliper, and which is normally maintained open by an arrangement of springs one of which opposes movement of the caliper under the drag force, the valve being arranged to be moved bodily by the drag force as brake pressure is increased and being subsequently prevented from returning by means responsive to supply pressure, whereupon reverse rotation of the caliper under incipient skid conditions causes the valve to close and pressure to be reduced in cylinders 6 either, as shown, by an expansion chamber 14 or by a relief valve. The fluid may be either hydraulic, supplied by a master cylinder or compressed air. In either case the valve consists of a body 9 which is slidable in a bracket 11 of the support 2, and a valve element 15 which is fluted to allow fluid flow past it along a bore 18 in which it slides, the head 16 of the valve element 15 normally being held clear of a seat, opening to a supply chamber 12, by a plunger 22 slidable in a bore 23 in the body and engaged at its remote end with the caliper, via a contact plate 26. A spring 29 urges the body 9 towards the caliper so that a stop 28 normally engages the head 16, and a spring 25 maintains the caliper normally in a position wherein stop pins 4 of the support 2 engage one end of slots 5 in the caliper. When pressure fluid is supplied to the chamber 12 it is also supplied to a locking or restraining device which as shown comprises a chamber 31 containing a friction pad 30 which is pressed by the fluid against the body to resist sliding movement. The friction produced by the pad 30 is overcome in normal braking by the drag force acting on the caliper 3 so that the valve is moved bodily by the plunger 22 acting via the element 15 and stop 28, compressing spring 25 in proportion to the drag force. Under incipient skid conditions, however, the caliper 3 reverses its movement while pad 30 holds the body 9 in its new position. The plunger 22 therefore retracts relative to the body 9, allowing a spring 17 to close the valve and, upon further retraction of plunger 22 in chamber 27, increasing the volume of the closed-off portion of the system to reduce pressure in the cylinders 6. In a modification (Fig. 2, not shown) the chamber 31 and pad 30 are replaced by a one-way valve 43 feeding fluid from a reservoir to a chamber 41 provided at the right-hand end of the body 9, and by a by-pass valve 46 for the valve 43 which is controlled by brake pressure.

column12: Improvements in or relating to optical projection systems
column13: 759,217. Optical systems. AMERICAN OPTICAL CO. May 28, 1954, No. 15908/54. Class 97 (1). A projection system comprises a plane mirror and a concave mirror facing one another, each mirror having a central aperture whereby light from the object passing through the aperture in one mirror is reflected by the second mirror back to the first mirror which in turn reflects the light through the aperture in the second mirror to form an image, an opaque baffle being located between the mirrors to intercept the major portion of the light passing directly through the two apertures. As shown, light from an object 1 such as a cathode-ray tube, passes through a central aperture 8 in a plane mirror 4 to reach a concave spherical mirror 3 from which it is reflected to the mirror 4 and thence directed through the central aperture 6 of the mirror 3 to form an image on a screen 7. A Schmidt plate 10 is provided in the aperture 6 to correct spherical aberration and an opaque baffle 9 prevents direct light from the object 1 reaching the screen 7. If desired, the baffle 9 may be dimensioned so as to allow some direct light to reach the screen to produce even illumination. A further diaphragm 12 may be provided. In a modification, the mirror 3 is replaced by a rear-surface reflecting lensmirror, correction being effected by lenses placed adjacent the mirror 3 between it and the screen 7. Alternatively the plate 10 may be replaced by a concentric meniscus lens convex to the mirror 4, or by a similar meniscus, convex to the screen 7 and located between the latter and the mirror 3.

Remapping inoperable memory blocks using pointers
column13: Inoperable bits are determined in a memory block. Rather than abandon the block as inoperable, a data structure is generated that includes at least one memory page pointer that identifies the location of the inoperable bits in the memory block. The data structure is stored in one of a group of memory blocks that are reserved for the data structures. A pointer to the data structure is stored in metadata associated with the memory block with the inoperable bits. When a later memory operation is received for the memory block, the pointer is retrieved from the metadata and the memory page pointers are used to avoid the inoperable bits.

column12: AUTOMOTIVE COLLISION AVOIDANCE AND/OR AIR BAG DEPLOYMENT RADAR
column13: A Doppler radar system for a vehicle providing driver warning, vehicle brake application and air bag deployment. The system produces voltage level inputs directed to the distance and approach rate to an object, vehicle speed and driving monitor inputs, such as steering angles, turning rates, braking, and acceleration/deacceleration. These voltages are properly weighted as to their importance. These weighted instantaneous input voltages are summed. The summed voltage is then compared with a predetermined voltage level dividing safe and danger zones. If the summed level falls within the safe zone, the radar system produces no output signals. If the summed voltage level falls within the danger zone, the radar system produces audio warning signals and if impact with an object is eminent vehicle braking signals are then produced. The invention further includes an air bag deployment feature. A vehicle air bag is deployed when the vehicle speed exceeds a pre-determined value and the distance to impact is within a predetermined distance. The air bag deployment and audio and braking functions are independent.

column13: A highly reliable shadow memory system is able to survive multiple fast sequence power failures and includes a volatile main memory and a shadow memory subsystem which continually monitors write accesses to the main memory. The shadow memory subsystem includes a disk drive or shadow memory storing a copy of the data in main memory. As the main memory contents are altered, the shadow memory is continually updated to reflect the changes while main utility power is available. In the event of a main utility power failure, backup power is required to store main memory data in the shadow memory for only a few storage locations for which the updating of theshadow memory may lagmain memory data changes. Consequently, only a small portion of available battery backup power is required to preserve all main memory data and the system can withstand multiple rapid succession power failures without loss of data.

column12: RADAR SYSTEM FOR HEADWAY CONTROL OF A VEHICLE
column13: A radar system for headway control of a vehicle comprises, an FM-CW radar for producing signals respectively representing the range and closing rate between the vehicle and an object. Signals are produced representing certain vehicle conditions including the speed, steering, acceleration and declaration of the vehicle. All of said signals are summed into a single signal representing the actual hazard level between the vehicle and the object. A reference signal is then produced representing a predetermined reference hazard level derived from summing weighted values of the range, closing rate and vehicle conditions. Finally, a signal is produced when the actual hazard level exceeds the reference hazard level. A signal representing road conditions, such as wet, dry, ice, snow conditions may be reflected in the actual and reference hazard levels.

APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR OIL AND FAT EXTRACTION
column13: An apparatus and method for extracting oils and fats from oil-bearing substances without using degrading temperatures. The apparatus may comprise an extraction chamber containing an oil-bearing substance, an oil-collecting chamber, a recovery pump, a first jacket adjacent at least a portion of the extraction chamber, and a second jacket adjacent at least a portion of the oil-collecting chamber. The method involves heating a solvent and reducing pressure to facilitate a low-temperature vacuum boil, delivering the heated solvent into the extraction chamber configured to facilitate the low-temperature vacuum boil of the solvent within the extraction chamber, pumping the solvent in vapor form out of the extraction chamber with the recovery pump, delivering the oil and fat extracted in the extraction chamber to the oil-collecting chamber, pumping solvent in vapor form out of the oil-collecting chamber with the recovery pump, and delivering the solvent received by the recovery pump to the first and second jackets to provide heat to the chambers.

[Also in Division F1] A booster-assisted hydraulic operating system, such as a braking system, comprises a manuallyoperated member 34 which actuates a piston 23 or the like for displacing fluid from a master cylinder 10 and, at the same time, actuates a valve or valves 47, 48 controlling the energization of a booster 16, 17 actuating another means 18 other than the piston 23 for increasing the displacement of fluid from the master cylinder when the booster is energized. The means 18 may be a hollow piston-rod which is secured to a piston 17 in the cylinder 16 of the booster, the cylinder being connected by a passage 38 to a valve chamber 22 which, at one end, has a valve 48 co-operating with a recess 44 joined by a passage 43 to a source of vacuum and connected by a passage 51 to a cylinder 52, the vacuum causing the rod 54 of a piston 53 in the cylinder to engage a groove 55 in a sleeve 37 so that the sleeve moves with the booster piston 17. The opposite end of the valve chamber has a valve 47 which co-operates with a recess 41 connected by a passage 39 to atmosphere. The valves 47, 48 are carried by a reduced part of a rod which is formed with the piston 23 and connected to the operating member 34. In the inoperative position, the valve 48 is closed and valve 47 is open to connect the booster cylinder to the atmosphere. Movement of the rod 34 causes the piston 23 to displace fluid from the master cylinder 10 through a port 14 leading to the brake cylinder and reverses the valves 47, 48 so that the vacuum is connected to the cylinder 16 and the piston 17 moves the hollow rod 18 to displace additional fluid from the cylinder 10. The initial movement of the piston also actuates a valve 27 to close a passage 12 leading from a reservoir 11 providing liquid to make-up for losses caused by leakage. In the event of failure of the source of vacuum, the piston-rod 54 is disengaged from the groove 55 to permit actuation of the piston 23 on its own. In other embodiments, the manually-operated and booster-operated pistons are separate and parallel, or the booster may move the master cylinder in the opposite direction to the manually-operated piston.

A signal lighting system for a vehicle includes a housing having an open front end. A bottom and top of the housing each have an arcuate front edge. The bottom extends farther forward than the top so the front edge of the bottom is in front of the front edge of the top. The system includes a plurality of lights between the bottom and top and positioned for directing light generally forward. Gaskets are at the front edges of the top and bottom of the housing for conforming the lighting system to a windshield of the vehicle. The lighting system is adjustable to facilitate mounting the lighting system in a wide range of different makes and models of vehicle notwithstanding differences that may exist between their windshield geometries. The lights may be included in light modules that can be rotationally adjusted while the system is mounted on the vehicle.

column12: MOLDING OF POLYPROPYLENE WITH ENHANCED REHEAT CHARACTERISTICS.
column13: Bottles, containers and other articles are formed from polypropylene compositions that include a reheating agent, such as antimony, carbon black, graphite, titanium, copper, manganese, iron, tungsten, graphite, infra-red absorbing dyes or other infra-red absorbing material. The reheating time for the polypropylene composition is shortened for injection stretch blow molding or thermoforming, and the polypropylene granule composition with reheating agent has an L* value of at least 80 % of the L* value for a polypropylene granule control without added reheating agents as measured by the Gardner color test. The reheating agent may be incorporated into the polypropylene composition by in situ chemical reduction of a metal compound, such as antimony triglycolate, with a reducing agent, such as hypophosphorous acid. In addition, the polypropylene composition with reheating agent may be derived from a polypropylene masterbatch with high concentrations of reheating agent.

Processo para a extração por solvente de óleos em um material contendo óleo, e, aparelho para a extração por solvente
column13: "PROCESSO PARA A EXTRAçãO POR SOLVENTE DE óLEOS EM UM MATERIAL CONTENDO óLEO, E, APARELHO PARA A EXTRAçãO POR SOLVENTE". Um processo para a extração de óleo por solvente, em uma câmara de extração, compreendendo a formação de uma névoa de solvente com capacidade de resfriamento adiabático significativo, onde uma diferença entre a entrada e a saída do solvente da câmara de extração direciona a névoa de solvente através da matéria prima contendo o óleo. O solvente é alimentado para a câmara de extração em pressões excedendo a pressão atmosférica, e a saída da câmara de extração é submetida a um vácuo parcial. Um aparelho para a extração por solvente é composto de uma câmara de extração para receber a matéria prima contendo óleo na mesma, a referida câmara de extração compreendendo um sistema de injeção por pulverização de um solvente conectado através de uma entrada com uma porção do circuito de alimentação de solvente de alta pressão, a referida câmara de extração conectada ainda através de uma saída com uma porção do circuito de baixa pressão conectado a um sistema de bomba a vácuo de recuperação de gás.

column12: Low wick continuous filament polyester yarn
column13: The present invention teaches a filament yarn that has low wicking, i.e., less than or equal to about 6 mm; has a contact angle of greater than or equal to about 65° but less than about 90° according to the straw method; and a static voltage of +/−400 volts (between −400 to +400 volts). Such yarns are traditionally employed in weaving signs, banners, awning, tents and other products where moisture resistant yarn is important. The yarns can be made into fabrics that possess the same features as the yarn, namely low wicking, and water and oil repellency.

column13: 1,037,321. Disc brakes. DUNLOP RUBBER CO. Ltd. Jan. 25, 1963 [Feb. 2, 1962], No. 4212/62. Heading F2E. A disc brake comprises a retractor member 48 having a pivotal connection with a non- rotatable part of the brake and a frictional clamp operable on the retractor member 48 and permitting pivotal movement thereof only on application of a force thereto greater than that exerted by the clamp. A resilient means 54 is connected between the retractor member 48 and a pressure member 28 associated with a friction element 19 of the brake to retract the friction element 19 a predetermined distance upon release of the brake. In the construction shown the pressure member 28 and the retractor member 48 are pivoted about a common pin. The normal brake movement is allowed by a peg 53 of the pressure member 28 moving in an elongated aperture 52 of the retractor member 48, the latter being pivoted on greater brake movement due to friction pad wear. The friction clamp assembly (Fig. 1, not shown) includes a pair of friction discs one on each side of the retractor member, a pair of clamping washers positioned about the friction discs and a securing nut and bolt, the bolt providing the abovementioned common pin. The friction discs are of smaller diameter than the washers and are sealed about their outer peripheries by rings of rubber or like resilient material. The brake is applied by a piston and cylinder arrangement 33, 34 through a connecting rod 32, the pressure member 28 being provided with a step 35 for co-operating with a pin 36 of the brake housing when the friction linings 23 are fully worn. The friction elements 19 are slidably held in the brake housing for movement parallel to the axis of the brake disc only.

Method and apparatus for heating a fluid
column13: Method and apparatus for heating a fluid, such as water, for any of several purposes, such as for use with carpet cleaning apparatus; and charcterized by supplying electrical current periodically to the primary of a conductive coil, thereby building and collapsing a field about a shorted electrically conductive secondary of the coil. The shorted secondary is a hollow conductor that is heated by high current flow. The heat is transferred to a fluid flowing through the hot, shorted secondary. In a specific aspect of the embodiment, a frame including spray nozzles, vacuum nozzles and the like has the apparatus for heating water connected into it such that heated water is supplied, to effect much more efficacious cleaning of carpets or similar floor surfaces. Also disclosed are specific details and preferred embodiments that have been constructed to date; particularly, the details of the apparatus in which the primary and the secondary coils are closely adjacent each other such that the I.sup.2 R heating that occurs in both the primary and secondary due to the building and collapsing of the field contribute to heating of the fluid passed through the fluid passageway in the secondary with the primary and secondary overwound on the same leg of the core, more of the flux that builds and collapses passes through both the primary and secondary so there is more heating of the fluid passing through the secondary. The hollow conductor of the secondary is deliberately shorted with a continuous weld so that there are an infinite number of elemental shorting bars whose I.sup.2 R losses produce greater heating of the fluid passed through the secondary.

column13: 1,190,573. Anti-skid br@ system for road vehicles. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 3 July, 1967 [5 July, 1966], No. 30121/66. Heading F2F. In an anti-skid braking system incorporating a skid sensing device arranged to release at least one of a vehicle's brakes to avoid locking, there is provided a sensitivity control valve 12 (Fig. 1) (detailed in Fig. 2) to control air pressure to the brake operating mechanism. The control valve 12 has an inlet port 24 connected to a reservoir 7 (Fig. 1) via a driver's valve 6 and an outlet 23 connected to a chamber 2 of brake operating mechanism 1. A restrictor member 25, movable by a diaphragm actuator 41 when supplied with air under pressure via inlet 13 and non-return valve 47 from a valve 9 when a plunger 10 therein is actuated by an inertia type skid sensor (not shown), provides a variable restriction to the flow of air through passage 22 for operating the brakes. The restrictor has a head 27 for engagement with a valve seat 28 and is provided with a recess 29 which permits only a restricted flow from inlet 24 to outlet 23 when head 27 is seated. The non-return valve 47 has a bleed orifice 50 to permit an exhaust flow of air from chamber 42 at a predetermined rate following each anti-skid operation. Anti-skid operation (Fig. 1).-When a skid is sensed plunger 10 of valve 9 is moved and causes air pressure from a reservoir 8 to be admitted to a chamber 3. Simultaneously air pressure is applied via line 13 to chamber 42 of actuator 41, thereby the restrictor member is moved to restrict flow to chamber 2. When the skid tendency is overcome plunger 10 is released and chamber 3 is connected to exhaust. The rise in pressure in chamber 2 is delayed by the restrictor to ensure that the rise does not occur in a period when anti-skid control valve 9 is operating cyclically to apply and release the brakes. Alternatively, the restrictor valve actuator may include a piston (Fig. 3, not shown) instead of a diaphragm, and a needle valve may be provided by means of which a restricted exhaust flow from the actuator is adjustable, to adjust the period of time in which the restrictor offers the greatest restriction. Specification 1,151,223 is referred to.

column12: Method and sensor for capturing rate and position and stabilization of a satellite using at least one focal plane
column13: An optical sensor includes dual fields of view including a panoramic field of view spanning 360 in azimuth angle in a direction perpendicular to an axis of the sensor, and a limb-looking field of view non-perpendicular to the axis for viewing the limb of the earth. Both fields of view are imaged onto annular regions of one of more focal plane arrays comprising pixels arranged in a rectangular array of rows and columns. The sensor is used in a method for capturing rate and direction of rotation of a satellite about its axes and for detecting orientation of the satellite about two of its axes. Rate and direction are determined by finding the center of the earth relative to axes of the focal plane array based on the image of the earth limb from the panoramic field of view, and comparing the earth center location at a series of sequential times. The rate and position information are used for stabilizing an initially tumbling satellite after tip-off. Once the satellite is stabilized, its orientation is detected by finding the earth center location on the focal plane array based on the earth limb image from the limb-looking optics of the sensor. In one embodiment of the invention, both fields of view are imaged onto concentric inner and outer ring-shaped regions of the same focal plane array.

column13: Engaging washers such as reaction washers and backup washers can include novel advantageous features. For example, an engaging washer can include an inner row of teeth and an outer row of teeth, where the teeth in the inner row can slope in a first circumferential direction to primarily engage a flange during bolt tightening, and the teeth in the outer row can slope in a second circumferential direction to primarily engage during bolt loosening. The engaging washers may also include an arched design to allow gradual increasing of contact surface areas as a clamping force in the washer gradually increases. Additionally, a reaction washer can include stepped castles for engaging a reaction socket. The castles may also include sloped or curved engaging surfaces that can provide decreased contact surface area and may also inhibit outward biasing of reaction fingers that are engaging the castles.

column12: SURGICAL STABILIZERS AND METHODS FOR USE IN REDUCED-ACCESS SURGICAL SITES
column13: Devices and methods for stabilizing tissue within a patient's body. Such a device is adapted to assume a reduced configuration and an operating configuration. The device assumes the reduced configuration for passage through a small opening to deliver a working end of the device to a site of the tissue to be stabilized. Such a device may include first and second contact members that are mounted for rotation, with each having a contact surface adapted to contact a surface of the tissue. When the device is in the operating configuration, a largest cross-sectional dimension of the contact members may be greater than a largest dimension of an opening through which the contact members were passed.. However, when in the reduced configuration, largest cross-sectional dimension of the contact members is less than the largest dimension of the opening.

column12: Aggressive data deduplication using lazy garbage collection
column13: A method for extending data lifetime for reference in deduplication is provided. The method includes determining that a quantity of user data has at least a threshold amount of data that is re-created in a storage system. column12: VACUUM PACKAGE WITH SMOOTH SURFACE AND METHOD OF MAKING SAME
column13: A vacuum package is made of flexible laminate capable of being stored as roll stock. The laminate comprises laminated inner (30) and outer (28) layers providing desired mechanical properties, secured together at patterned areas (36(a)-44(a) to facilitate the pasage of gas between the layers, and is provided with a hand peelable sealing strip (60) at an area which, when the laminate is formed into a bag and the mouth sealed, extends around the periphery of the mouth of the package. When the laminate is formed into a bag, the application of vacuum to the interior of the bag results in the inner layer conforming to the contours of the contents, while ambient air between the layers enables the outer layer to maintain a desirable and aesthetically pleasing smooth surface texture.

column12: Automotive collision avoidance and/or air bag deployment radar.
column13: A Doppler radar system for a vehicle providing driver warning, vehicle brake application and air bag deployment. The system produces voltage level inputs directed to the distance and approach rate to an object, vehicle speed and driving monitor inputs, such as steering angles, turning rates, braking, and acceleration/deacceleration. These voltages are properly weighted as to their importance. These weighted instantaneous input voltages are summed. The summed voltage is then compared with a predetermined voltage level dividing safe and danger zones. If the summed level falls within the safe zone, the radar system produces no output signals. If the summed voltage level falls within the danger zone, the radar system produces audio warning signals and if impact with an object is eminent vehicle braking signals are then produced. The invention further includes an air bag deployment feature. A vehicle air bag is deployed when the vehicle speed exceeds a pre-determined value and the distance to impact is within a predetermined distance. The air bag deployment and audio and braking functions are independent.

A metal retainer spring bent into a forwardly tapered flexible spring for retaining an acoustic ear tube for use with behind-the-ear devices. A rearward hook or tapering slot holds the acoustic ear tube with a friction fit. A forward opening admits the acoustic ear tube therethrough to transmit sound to the eardrum. The ear canal-contacting surfaces of each spring have a friction surface to limit slippage without causing abrasions.

column12: CONSTRUCCION MEJORADA DE UNA TORRE DE REFRIGERACION.
column13: Construcción mejorada de una torre de enfriamiento de un líquido. La torre incluye una pared exterior impermeable y una pared interior flexible y permeable al aire separada hacia el interior desde la pared exterior para definir una cámara entre las dos paredes. La pared interior permeable al aire presenta una multiplicidad de poros a través de los cuales puede pasar el aire con el fin de eliminar depósitos de la cara interna de la pared interior. Está previsto un medio de suministro para inyectar aire al interior de la camara entre las dos paredes y otro medio de suministro inyecta aire al interior del volumen interno dentro de la pared interior, siendo este el aire de enfriamiento. Otro medio pulveriza el líquido en el volumen interno rodeado por la pared interior. Para proporcionar aire a presión en la cámara anular están previstas aberturas en la pared exterior y una cámara impelente, externa a la pared interior, comunica con las aberturas de manera que a través de la inyección de aire al interior de la cámara impelente aquel pasará automáticamente a la camara anular y desde aquí a través de los poros de la pared interior, con el fin de limpiar de depósitos la pared interior.

A system enables a service provider to provide real time, on-line help to a web page user. When the web page user initiates a help request, a client agent may automatically provide a service provider with information, about the particular web page that is causing the problem, sufficient to enable the service provider to access the web page. The agent also initiates a chat session between the service provider and the client. In this way, the service provider can see the actual web page that is causing the problem and may communicate through the chat session channel with the user. In one embodiment, a chat session dialog box may overlie the associated web page.

A wellhead retrieval tool is disclosed which is adaptable to a variety of configurations of wellheads. The tool comprises a spear through which a rotary cutter can operate. The tool can be adjustably supported off the top of the wellhead so that the grappling mechanism can be located at the proper distance for a grip on an inward upset or restriction within the wellhead. The clutching mechanism is located outside of the wellhead so as not to contaminate it with cuttings returned with the circulating fluid. The seal bore in the wellhead is protected by the tool to avoid damage. The dogs which engage the internal inward upset or restriction further have wickers or serrations on them to enhance the grip and to resist applied torque.

Engaging washers such as reaction washers and backup washers can include novel advantageous features. For example, an engaging washer can include an inner row of teeth and an outer row of teeth, where the teeth in the inner row can slope in a first circumferential direction to primarily engage a flange during bolt tightening, and the teeth in the outer row can slope in a second circumferential direction to primarily engage during bolt loosening. The engaging washers may also include an arched design to allow gradual increasing of contact surface areas as a clamping force in the washer gradually increases. Additionally, a reaction washer can include stepped castles for engaging a reaction socket. The castles may also include sloped or curved engaging surfaces that can provide decreased contact surface area and may also inhibit outward biasing of reaction fingers that are engaging the castles.

column13: 1,024,851. Disc brakes. DUNLOP RUBBER CO Ltd. Aug. 23, 1962 [Sept. 2, 1961], No. 31621/61. Heading F2E. A disc brake comprises a non-rotatable brake housing 10 having an abutment face 29 to resist circumferential movement of a friction element 19 in the plane of a rotatable disc 11 and means 22 for forcing the element into frictional engagement with the disc. The friction element, Fig. 4 (not shown), has a shape which is produced when one radial end of a segment is cut off and positioned so that the erst-while radial edges abut. As shown, the pads 19 are forced against the disc by pressure members 14, 15, which are pivoted at 16 to the housing 10 and extend at a slight angle to each other. Convex protrusions 17 on the members 14, 15 bear on the backing plate 18. The pressure members are actuated by a pistoncylinder mechanism 22, a pivoted lever 21 and a tie-rod 20 having an automatic adjuster 26. A pair of springy but deformable fingers 34, the ends of which are engaged in holes 35 in the members 14, 15 are provided to retract the members 14, 15 after each brake application but are capable of being progressively deformed as wear of the pads 19 takes place. Springs 36 between the backing plate 18 and the fingers 34 retract the pads. Tongues 27, Fig. 2 (not shown), on, and bent at right-angles to the backing plates, which tongues are a slidable fit in a slot 33 in a keep member 32, and projections 30 on the backing plates engaged in recesses 32, retain the trailing edge 28 of the pad in abutting relationship with the face 29. A measure of damping which tends to eliminate brake squeal is provided due to the contact of the friction material itself with the abutment face. The lever 21 may be actuated by mechanical as well as by, or alternatively to, the pistoncylinder mechanism 22. Alternatively, hydraulic piston-cylinder assemblies on each side of the disc may be provided to actuate the pads. Other shapes of pads are described wherein the trailing abutting edge is arcuate having the centroid of the friction element as its centre.

column13: 964,496. Fluid pressure brakes; indicators. GIRLING Ltd. Oct. 5, 1960 [Aug. 1, 1959], No. 26493/59. Headings F2E and F2F. A pedal operated booster-assisted braking system for a vehicle incorporates a master cylinder so that on failure of the booster the capacity of the master cylinder is increased to provide the pedal with a length of travel greater than normal during application of the brake. A pedal operated rod 25 in normal use shifts inwardly a piston 23 having shoulders 26 and 27 which close one valve 38 previously venting a booster cylinder 16 through a port 31, and opens another valve 39 connecting the cylinder 16 through a path 29, 38 and 34 to a vacuum source 37. A booster piston 17 and an integral piston 18 operating in a master cylinder 10 are moved forward, the consequent increase in pressure closing a reservoir valve 54 and pressurizing a brake line 14. The booster piston 17 and pedal operated piston 23 are normally locked together by a radial latch-pin 45 which is maintained by the vacuum source 37 acting on a piston 44 in engagement with a groove in a sleeve 28 fast with the piston 23, the piston 44 being slidable in a radial cylinder fast with the piston 17. Failure of the vacuum allows a spring to raise the latch pin 45 whereupon a spring 53 urges the piston 23 outwardly to raise the brake pedal which subsequently when applied moves only the piston 23 in the master cylinder so that the fluid displacement is less than normal, the pedal pressure being smaller and pedal movement greater.

column13: 1,222,510. Inertia switches. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 24 April, 1968 [25 April, 1967], No 18973/67. Heading F2F. [Also in Division H1] An inertia-type deceleration responsive device e.g. for an anti-skid system comprises a flywheel 11, Fig. 2, mounted in an annular housing 2 on the gear-box output shaft 5. Teeth inside the flywheel mesh with three equally spaced gearwheels 9 driving cylindrical cams 8 having an inclined end surface 21 co-operating with tubular cams 20 to impart axial movement to a switching member 25 when the flywheel overruns the housing. The switch may be a magnetic reed switch, a pneumatic sensing device operating a switch or a light switch (arrangements are exemplified in the Specification). The switch is connected in a brake control circuit to release the brakes. In a modification, Fig. 8 (not shown), the teeth on the flywheel are formed on its outer periphery so that the flywheel lies within the gearwheels. In a second embodiment, Fig. 9 and Fig. 10 (not shown), a pinion 52 is secured to the cam member 57, on which the flywheel 50 is mounted, and meshes with teeth on the inner periphery 53 of an annular disc 54 provided with a series of magnets 56 on its circumference. A reed switch 60 is mounted on a stationary member 61 between magnets 56 and a second set 59 on an annular member 58 rotating with the housing 55. The arrangement of magnets is such that when the flywheel and housing rotate together, the reed switch is maintained open but is closed when the flywheel overruns the housing, as illustrated in Figs. 11, 12 (not shown). In another embodiment the flywheel is mounted on three flanged pulleys, Fig. 6 (not shown). An axially movable annular member (40) equivalent to member 25 in embodiment of Fig. 2, is connected with the flywheel by a thrust friction arrangement (41). In a further embodiment, Fig. 14, an annular flange 80 is mounted in the housing for limited angular movement relative thereto and is additionally connected between the flywheel 76 and housing by buttons 82 of friction material which contact the flywheel at one end and ramp surfaces 84 on the housing such that when the flywheel overruns the flange 80 is rotated with it a short distance. The flange 80 is connected to an axially slidable flange 85 by rods 94, Fig. 16 (not shown), so that on relative angular movement between the two flanges, caused by flywheel overrun, the flange 85 is moved towards the flange 80, causing a magnetic reed switch 90 to be closed.

column12: One trip multiple string section milling of subterranean tubulars
column13: Multiple section mills are run in a single trip with an intervening mill preferably a watermelon mill to grind up any cuttings that get past the first mill in a direction toward the second mill below it. The blades of the second mill are held by the innermost tubular until the location of the initial cut is reached at which point the longer arms of the second mill can be extended and its body centralizes due to the flexibility of the connection between the mills.

Embodiments are disclosed for network devices and metadata transmission/receipt in a network. An example network device in a daisy-chain or ring network includes a network interface device, a processor, and a storage device storing instructions executable by the processor to allocate a channel in the network as a metadata channel, and synchronize with each other device in the network. The instructions are further executable to insert metadata into a metadata packet, and transmit the metadata packet on the allocated metadata channel alongside content transmitted on remaining channels of the network.

column12: TITANIUM DIOXIDE PARTICLES WITH ADHERING DISCRETE INORGANIC PARTICLES
column13: The present invention relates to TiO2 pigments having TiO2 particles with substantially discrete inorganic particles dispersed on the surfaces of the TiO2 particles. Suitable inorganic particles include silica, calcium carbonate, and mixtures thereof. The substantially discrete inorganic particles have an average diameter size within the range of about 5 to about 50 nm and are dispersed on the surfaces of the TiO2 particles in an amount of less than 20 wt.% based on total pigment weight. This invention also includes coating compositions containing these pigments and processes for making these pigments.

column12: Process for preparing a silicon melt
column13: A process for controlling the amount of insoluble gas trapped by a silicon melt is disclosed. After a crucible is charged with polycrystalline silicon, a gas comprising at least about 10% of a gas having a high solubility in silicon is used as the purging gas for a period of time during melting. After the polycrystalline silicon charge has completely melted, the purge gas may be switched to a conventional argon purge. Utilizing a purge gas highly soluble in silicon for a period of time during the melting process reduces the amount of insoluble gases trapped in the charge and, hence, the amount of insoluble gases grown into the crystal that form defects on sliced wafers.

column12: SURFACE SIGNAL FOR FLOW BLOCKAGE FOR A SUBTERRANEAN DEBRIS COLLECTION APPARATUS
column13: The debris collection device operates on an eductor principle with motive fluid delivered from the surface into an eductor housing inlet. The eductor outlet goes into a surrounding annular space and splits with some flow going to the mill below to direct cuttings into the passage in the housing. The cuttings remain in the housing and the flow continues through a screen in the housing passage before reaching the eductor inlet. An auxiliary inlet is normally closed and opened with a reduced flow entering through the mill. The opening of the auxiliary inlet drops the surface pressure delivered to the eductor to act as a surface signal that a plugged or low debris laden inlet flow exists.

Knives, cleaning and polishing.-The knives are inserted between two horizontal boards of which the upper D, fitted with a box F containing knifecleaning powder which can reach the polishing- surfaces G, E by means of an opening H, is mounted between standards C, C<1> and can be raised readily to admit the knife and to facilitate the entrance of the powder between the surfaces by shaking. Strips of leather are provided on the top of the upper board for cleaning the backs of the knives. In a modification with three boards and two pairs of polishing-surfaces, the powder falls from the box to the first pair, and then by other holes to the second pair ; a gutter serves to collect the waste powder. A box may be fitted below the second board so as to make the apparatus reversible.

column12: AGGRESSIVE DATA DEDUPLICATION USING LAZY GARBAGE COLLECTION
column13: A method for extending data lifetime for reference in deduplication is provided. The method includes determining that a quantity of user data has at least a threshold amount of data that is re-created in a storage system. The method includes protecting at least portions of the quantity of user data from erasure by garbage collection in the storage system during a predetermined time interval, wherein the protected at least portions are available for data deduplication of further user data in the storage system during the predetermined time interval.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR OIL AND FAT EXTRACTION
column13: An apparatus and method for extracting oils and fats from oil-bearing substances without using degrading temperatures. The apparatus may comprise an extraction chamber containing an oil-bearing substance, an oil-collecting chamber, a recovery pump, a first jacket adjacent at least a portion of the extraction chamber, and a second jacket adjacent at least a portion of the oil-collecting chamber. The method involves heating a solvent and reducing pressure to facilitate a low-temperature vacuum boil, delivering the heated solvent into the extraction chamber configured to facilitate the low-temperature vacuum boil of the solvent within the extraction chamber, pumping the solvent in vapor form out of the extraction chamber with the recovery pump, delivering the oil and fat extracted in the extraction chamber to the oil-collecting chamber, pumping solvent in vapor form out of the oil-collecting chamber with the recovery pump, and delivering the solvent received by the recovery pump to the first and second jackets to provide heat to the chambers.

A modular building formed from non-combustible materials which includes a support frame. The frame includes subflooring with a connected concrete pan which allows the concrete floor to be directly into the frame. The building also includes roof edge supports for connecting beams which allow two or more buildings to be joined to form a single complex.

column12: Swivel Wheel Mounting For A Scooter
column13: Scooters typically have a fixed rear wheel and a rotating front wheel on a length forming a handle. Such scooters are not always able to be used to perform tricks and stunts because they have a fixed rear wheel that can inhibit this. In particular many children and adults wish to drift the rear wheel, or have it at oblique angle to the scooter's direction of movement. The present invention provides a scooter wheel mounting capable of forming in use a two wheeled scooter, wherein the rear wheel being provided on a rotatable seat.

column13: A doppler radar module consisting of transmitting and receiving diodes disposed within adjacent sections of waveguide with the transmitter diode disposed a half wavelength away from a shorting end of the transmitter section of wavelength and a receiver diode disposed a quarter wave from a shorting end of the receiver portion of the waveguide. A cover is provided for a launder, or an equivalent open-topped vessel for containing molten metal, the cover including a heat-insulative layer spanning the open top of the vessel, with a spacer arrangement to maintain a gap of uniform width between the heat-insulative layer and the open-top. A housing defines an evacuation plenum, and connections are made to allow an exhaust device to remove gaseous materials from the plenum. Adjacent the gap is an air-guide arrangement which directs outside air into the evacuation chamber along a path which is intercepted by any gaseous materials exiting through the gap, whereby such gaseous materials are entrained into the evacuation chamber.
